5.4.2 Tutorial: Project with Parallel Tasks
-------------------------------------------

Let's create a project where some tasks can happen simultaneously.

   • The Scenario

     You need to "Fix Shoulder Pain":
       1. Find MRI facility (research task)
       2. Make MRI appointment (depends on finding facility)
       3. Make orthopedist appointment (independent research - can
          happen in parallel with 1 & 2)
       4. Get diagnosis (depends on both appointments completing)

     Tasks 1 and 3 can happen in parallel - they don't depend on each
     other.

   • Step 1: Capture the Project

     ‘C-c d c’ to capture:

          * Fix Shoulder Pain
          ** Find place to get MRI
          ** Make MRI appointment
          ** Make orthopedist appointment
          ** Get diagnosis from orthopedist

   • Step 2: Organize with Custom Dependencies

     After organizing as a project (‘C-c c’ → ‘[P]’), org-gtd creates
     sequential dependencies by default.  We need to modify them for
     parallel execution.

     **Open the project file:**

     Find your project in the engage view (‘C-c d e’), press ‘RET’ on
     any task to jump to the project file.

     **The project looks like this:**

          * Fix Shoulder Pain
          :PROPERTIES:
          :ORG_GTD: Projects
          :ORG_GTD_FIRST_TASKS: <id-of-find-mri>
          :END:
          ** NEXT Find place to get MRI
          :PROPERTIES:
          :ID: <id-of-find-mri>
          :ORG_GTD: Actions
          :ORG_GTD_BLOCKS: <id-of-make-mri-appt>
          :END:
          ** TODO Make MRI appointment
          :PROPERTIES:
          :ID: <id-of-make-mri-appt>
          :ORG_GTD: Actions
          :ORG_GTD_DEPENDS_ON: <id-of-find-mri>
          :ORG_GTD_BLOCKS: <id-of-make-ortho-appt>
          :END:
          ** TODO Make orthopedist appointment
          ... (and so on, sequential)

   • Step 3: Modify for Parallel Execution

     We want "Find MRI place" and "Make orthopedist appointment" to be
     parallel starting tasks.

     **On the project heading**, add the orthopedist appointment ID to
     FIRST_TASKS:

          :ORG_GTD_FIRST_TASKS: <id-of-find-mri> <id-of-make-ortho-appt>

     **On "Make orthopedist appointment" task**, remove the DEPENDS_ON
     property:

     Remove the line: ‘:ORG_GTD_DEPENDS_ON: <id-of-make-mri-appt>’

     **On "Get diagnosis" task**, make it depend on BOTH appointments:

          :ORG_GTD_DEPENDS_ON: <id-of-make-mri-appt> <id-of-make-ortho-appt>

     **Fix the BLOCKS properties:**
        • Remove orthopedist appointment from MRI appointment's BLOCKS
        • Add diagnosis ID to both appointment tasks' BLOCKS

   • Step 4: Fix Keywords

     Put point on the project heading and run:

     ‘M-x org-gtd-projects-fix-todo-keywords-for-project-at-point’

     This recalculates which tasks should be NEXT based on the
     dependency graph.

   • Step 5: See the Results

     ‘C-c d e’ to view the engage agenda.

     You'll now see:
        • *NEXT: Find place to get MRI*
        • *NEXT: Make orthopedist appointment*

     Both are NEXT simultaneously!  You can work on whichever you want.

     When you complete both appointments, "Get diagnosis" automatically
     becomes NEXT.

   • The Dependency Pattern (Diamond)

     This is called a "diamond" pattern:

              Find MRI ─────┐
                            ├──→ Get Diagnosis
          Make Ortho Appt ──┘

     Two parallel paths converge at a single task.  This is common in
     real projects.


