5.4.4 Common Dependency Patterns
--------------------------------

   • Sequential Chain (A → B → C)

     The simplest pattern.  Default for all projects.

     Use when: Order matters, each task depends on the previous.

     Example: Review blueprints → Order windows → Schedule carpenter

   • Parallel Independent (A, B, C all start together)

     All tasks are in FIRST_TASKS, no dependencies between them.

     Use when: Tasks are completely independent and can all start
     immediately.

     Example: Research destinations, Check budget, Ask for time off (for
     vacation planning)

   • Fan-out (A → B, A → C, A → D)

     One task blocks multiple tasks that can then proceed in parallel.

     Use when: Initial work enables multiple independent paths.

     Example: Get project approval → (Design UI, Write backend API,
     Setup infrastructure)

   • Fan-in / Convergence (A → C, B → C)

     Multiple tasks must complete before next task can start.  Also
     called "join".

     Use when: Final task needs all previous work completed.

     Example: (Write code, Write tests) → Merge to main

   • Diamond (A → B → D, A → C → D)

     Parallel paths that converge.  Combination of fan-out and fan-in.

     Use when: Work splits, proceeds in parallel, then combines.

     Example: Research → (Write content, Design graphics) → Publish
     article


