6.3.1 Core GTD Properties
-------------------------

   • ORG_GTD

     *Used on*: All GTD items (projects, actions, calendar items,
     incubated items, etc.)

     *Purpose*: Identifies the type of GTD item

     *Values*:
     ‘"Projects"’
          Project heading
     ‘"Actions"’
          Project tasks and single actions
     ‘"Calendar"’
          Calendar items (appointments, deadlines)
     ‘"Incubated"’
          Someday/maybe items
     ‘"Delegated"’
          Delegated tasks (set in combination with DELEGATED_TO)

     *Example*:
          * My Project
          :PROPERTIES:
          :ORG_GTD: Projects
          :END:
          ** NEXT Task 1
          :PROPERTIES:
          :ORG_GTD: Actions
          :END:

     *Note*: This property is how org-gtd identifies items.  Don't
     modify manually unless you understand the implications.


File: org-gtd.info,  Node: Project Properties,  Next: Task Dependency Properties,  Prev: Core GTD Properties,  Up: Properties Reference

6.3.2 Project Properties
------------------------

   • ORG_GTD_FIRST_TASKS

     *Used on*: Project headings

     *Purpose*: Identifies which tasks can start immediately (have no
     dependencies)

     *Format*: Space-separated list of task IDs

     *Example*:
          * Software Release
          :PROPERTIES:
          :ORG_GTD: Projects
          :ORG_GTD_FIRST_TASKS: abc123 def456
          :END:

     This means tasks with IDs "abc123" and "def456" can both start
     immediately (parallel execution).

     *When to modify*:
        • After organizing a project (org-gtd sets this automatically)
        • When adding parallel starting points to a project
        • Always run
          ‘org-gtd-projects-fix-todo-keywords-for-project-at-point’
          after manual edits


File: org-gtd.info,  Node: Task Dependency Properties,  Next: Calendar and Time Properties,  Prev: Project Properties,  Up: Properties Reference

6.3.3 Task Dependency Properties
--------------------------------

   • ORG_GTD_DEPENDS_ON

     *Used on*: Project tasks

     *Purpose*: Lists task IDs that must complete before this task can
     start

     *Format*: Space-separated list of task IDs

     *Example*:
          ** NEXT Get project approval
          :PROPERTIES:
          :ID: task-001
          :ORG_GTD: Actions
          :ORG_GTD_BLOCKS: task-002 task-003
          :END:
          ** TODO Design solution
          :PROPERTIES:
          :ID: task-002
          :ORG_GTD: Actions
          :ORG_GTD_DEPENDS_ON: task-001
          :ORG_GTD_BLOCKS: task-004
          :END:
          ** TODO Setup infrastructure
          :PROPERTIES:
          :ID: task-003
          :ORG_GTD: Actions
          :ORG_GTD_DEPENDS_ON: task-001
          :ORG_GTD_BLOCKS: task-004
          :END:
          ** TODO Implement feature
          :PROPERTIES:
          :ID: task-004
          :ORG_GTD: Actions
          :ORG_GTD_DEPENDS_ON: task-002 task-003
          :END:

     In this example:
        • Task 001 (approval) starts first
        • Tasks 002 (design) and 003 (infrastructure) can run in
          parallel after approval
        • Task 004 (implement) waits for both 002 and 003 to complete

     *When to modify*:
        • When creating custom dependency structures
        • When changing task relationships
        • Always update ORG_GTD_BLOCKS on the blocking tasks too
          (bidirectional)
        • Always run
          ‘org-gtd-projects-fix-todo-keywords-for-project-at-point’
          after edits

   • ORG_GTD_BLOCKS

     *Used on*: Project tasks

     *Purpose*: Lists task IDs that depend on this task completing
     (inverse of DEPENDS_ON)

     *Format*: Space-separated list of task IDs

     *Relationship*: If task A has ‘ORG_GTD_BLOCKS: B C’, then:
        • Task B should have ‘ORG_GTD_DEPENDS_ON: A’
        • Task C should have ‘ORG_GTD_DEPENDS_ON: A’

     *When to modify*:
        • Manually when setting up dependencies (maintain bidirectional
          relationship)
        • Use ‘org-gtd-task-add-dependent’ command instead of manual
          edits when possible

   • ORG_GTD_PROJECT_IDS

     *Used on*: Tasks

     *Purpose*: Lists project IDs this task belongs to (supports
     multi-project tasks)

     *Format*: Space-separated list of project IDs

     *Note*: Currently org-gtd creates one project per task, but this
     property supports future multi-project features.


